1
00:00:13,620 --> 00:00:16,817
<i>In February 2002, an independent
unit interviewed Fidel Castro.</i>

2
00:00:16,980 --> 00:00:19,540
<i>He was offered the power
to cut and erase at any time.</i>

3
00:00:19,700 --> 00:00:23,216
<i>Over the course of 3 days and nights
Mr. Castro never chose to cut.</i>

4
00:00:23,420 --> 00:00:25,934
<i>What follows is culled
from 30 hours of conversation.</i>

5
00:01:10,340 --> 00:01:12,854
<i>First films of Cuban rebel leader
Fidel Castro.</i>

6
00:01:13,020 --> 00:01:14,931
<i>Castro's plan of action</i>

7
00:01:15,100 --> 00:01:17,774
<i>to fight by any means until
the Batista regime is toppled.</i>

8
00:01:17,940 --> 00:01:20,500
<i>Behind Batista stand
the army, the police and,</i>

9
00:01:20,660 --> 00:01:21,855
<i>apparently, Cuba's labor unions.</i>

10
00:01:22,020 --> 00:01:25,695
<i>Batista seemed upset
about reports in the American press</i>

11
00:01:25,860 --> 00:01:28,534
<i>of police brutality
and corruption but confident</i>

12
00:01:28,700 --> 00:01:30,293
<i>in the face of
an unpredictable future.</i>

13
00:01:38,660 --> 00:01:41,015
<i>This is the band
that for 16 months</i>

14
00:01:41,180 --> 00:01:43,251
<i>has held out in the rugged
Sierra Maestre mountains</i>

15
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:45,093
<i>near the island's eastern tip.</i>

16
00:01:45,260 --> 00:01:47,410
<i>Ill-supplied, they make
many of their weapons</i>

17
00:01:47,580 --> 00:01:49,457
<i>in crude jungle workshops.</i>

18
00:01:52,540 --> 00:01:54,292
<i>The ragged, underfed,
poorly-armed rebels</i>

19
00:01:54,460 --> 00:01:56,690
<i>cut off communications
and supply lines</i>

20
00:01:56,860 --> 00:02:00,330
<i>in a campaign of sniping
and sabotage. Castro himself</i>

21
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:02,537
<i>has become a figure of legend</i>

22
00:02:02,700 --> 00:02:04,452
<i>since he invaded Oriente province</i>

23
00:02:04,620 --> 00:02:06,054
<i>from a small boat.
It is</i>

24
00:02:06,220 --> 00:02:08,780
<i>an unequal battle of idealists
against tough professional forces.</i>

25
00:02:09,380 --> 00:02:12,179
<i>Says Castro, “If I lose,
PH start over again.</i>

26
00:02:12,420 --> 00:02:14,377
<i>If Batista loses,
he loses for good.“</i>

27
00:02:16,580 --> 00:02:20,938
JANUARY 1959, HAVANA, CUBA

28
00:02:22,180 --> 00:02:23,090
<i>Tyranny</i>

29
00:02:25,340 --> 00:02:26,978
<i>has been vanquished.</i>

30
00:02:30,300 --> 00:02:32,291
<i>The joy is overwhelming.</i>

31
00:02:35,580 --> 00:02:36,854
<i>Nevertheless,</i>

32
00:02:38,380 --> 00:02:40,656
<i>there is still much to do.</i>

33
00:02:44,900 --> 00:02:46,538
<i>Our political philosophy</i>

34
00:02:47,540 --> 00:02:49,178
<i>is representative</i>

35
00:02:49,340 --> 00:02:50,819
<i>democracy</i>

36
00:02:50,980 --> 00:02:54,530
<i>and social justice
in a well-planned</i>

37
00:02:54,700 --> 00:02:55,690
<i>ECONOMY.</i>

38
00:03:01,060 --> 00:03:02,539
The Cuban revolution.

39
00:03:03,180 --> 00:03:05,251
It was a small island,
a small revolution.

40
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:07,259
But it goes through time.

41
00:03:08,140 --> 00:03:09,494
There is a discrepancy...

42
00:03:10,580 --> 00:03:11,900
A small island,

43
00:03:13,260 --> 00:03:15,376
a big revolution.

44
00:03:20,540 --> 00:03:22,451
If today you had not succeeded,

45
00:03:23,740 --> 00:03:25,219
would you be on a soapbox

46
00:03:25,380 --> 00:03:28,418
now in the park,
talking about revolution?

47
00:03:30,140 --> 00:03:31,892
No, I would be dead.

48
00:03:47,860 --> 00:03:48,975
<i>When we have</i>

49
00:03:49,140 --> 00:03:53,896
<i>fulfilled our promise
of a new government,</i>

50
00:03:54,060 --> 00:03:55,937
<i>I will cut my beard.</i>

51
00:03:56,940 --> 00:03:58,578
Let me take a closer look
at myself.

52
00:03:58,740 --> 00:04:00,697
If I get close...

53
00:04:01,380 --> 00:04:03,257
Let me see
where it looks best.

54
00:04:04,540 --> 00:04:05,496
You guys

55
00:04:05,660 --> 00:04:09,494
should do what your boss says.

56
00:04:09,660 --> 00:04:10,695
And me too.

57
00:04:13,500 --> 00:04:14,820
PALACE OF THE REVOLUTION,
HAVANA, CUBA

58
00:04:14,860 --> 00:04:18,330
At any point, if he says "Cut"
or I say "Cut"

59
00:04:18,500 --> 00:04:20,218
or we both say "Cut"...
either one,

60
00:04:20,380 --> 00:04:22,769
you stop and we'll talk.

61
00:04:22,940 --> 00:04:25,170
Maybe he wants to go again,
like an actor.

62
00:04:25,340 --> 00:04:26,694
He gets a second take
and let's go again.

63
00:04:26,860 --> 00:04:29,978
This is an acting exercise
that he will fail.

64
00:04:30,140 --> 00:04:33,451
And after that we'll go into
a completely spontaneous mode.

65
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:38,494
Okay, action.

66
00:04:39,140 --> 00:04:42,417
Commander, it's late
but you need to sign these.

67
00:04:42,580 --> 00:04:43,570
What are you saying?

68
00:04:45,940 --> 00:04:48,534
I can sign just a few.

69
00:04:52,140 --> 00:04:54,177
With just a few we'll move ahead.

70
00:05:01,140 --> 00:05:03,370
What's the longest
he's written recently?

71
00:05:07,060 --> 00:05:11,338
The longest things I've written
recently are speeches for T.V.

72
00:05:12,060 --> 00:05:13,778
You don't write poetry?

73
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:17,211
No, but when I write,
I like the words

74
00:05:18,020 --> 00:05:20,216
to have a certain harmony.

75
00:05:21,380 --> 00:05:23,098
I like combining words

76
00:05:24,820 --> 00:05:27,016
so there's a cadence, a rhythm,

77
00:05:27,180 --> 00:05:28,375
when I write them down.

78
00:05:29,140 --> 00:05:31,939
I could produce so much more

79
00:05:33,300 --> 00:05:34,176
by talking.

80
00:05:36,340 --> 00:05:37,774
Who knows the thousands

81
00:05:39,980 --> 00:05:42,449
of episodes, anecdotes, I've told.

82
00:05:44,780 --> 00:05:46,214
How much of your day

83
00:05:46,580 --> 00:05:49,572
is spent on administrative,
how much on

84
00:05:49,740 --> 00:05:54,132
creative and how much of your day
is spent on physical maintenance?

85
00:06:01,780 --> 00:06:04,499
The least possible on
administrative matters.

86
00:06:06,620 --> 00:06:10,579
The most on speaking with comrades,

87
00:06:11,100 --> 00:06:13,660
discussing different issues.

88
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:15,654
Is that creative?

89
00:06:16,700 --> 00:06:19,977
Yes, because we find
solutions to problems.

90
00:06:21,220 --> 00:06:22,893
One should...

91
00:06:23,980 --> 00:06:25,573
gather information.

92
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:28,889
Get to know problems.

93
00:06:29,820 --> 00:06:31,936
And try to find solutions.

94
00:06:32,380 --> 00:06:35,532
- There are all kinds of problems.
-What about maintenance?

95
00:06:37,620 --> 00:06:40,658
I don't waste
any time shaving.

96
00:06:40,820 --> 00:06:42,891
I once calculated...

97
00:06:44,260 --> 00:06:46,410
the meaning...

98
00:06:49,460 --> 00:06:52,134
that I saved months
of my life that way...

99
00:06:52,580 --> 00:06:56,460
Assuming it takes
15 minutes to shave.

100
00:06:58,180 --> 00:07:00,137
When I was...

101
00:07:01,940 --> 00:07:02,930
a young man...

102
00:07:03,940 --> 00:07:06,216
I spent a lot of time on sports.

103
00:07:09,260 --> 00:07:10,739
The pleasure of sport.

104
00:07:13,060 --> 00:07:16,451
Nowadays, the maintenance I do

105
00:07:18,380 --> 00:07:19,609
is to stay healthy.

106
00:07:20,900 --> 00:07:22,538
This office is my track.

107
00:07:27,300 --> 00:07:29,211
I measure the number of steps.

108
00:07:31,220 --> 00:07:33,450
Can you show us a circle?

109
00:07:36,580 --> 00:07:37,570
Right away.

110
00:07:40,980 --> 00:07:41,651
First,

111
00:07:41,820 --> 00:07:43,140
I look at my watch...

112
00:07:45,980 --> 00:07:47,778
I check my pulse.

113
00:07:52,460 --> 00:07:53,689
Then...

114
00:07:53,860 --> 00:07:55,089
I start walking.

115
00:07:58,780 --> 00:08:01,499
He counts his steps...
it's like a prisoner a bit.

116
00:08:03,500 --> 00:08:04,729
I've no other choice.

117
00:08:04,900 --> 00:08:06,049
I'm a prisoner.

118
00:08:06,860 --> 00:08:09,818
When I come in here...
this is a cell.

119
00:08:21,420 --> 00:08:24,651
When he gets bad news,
how does he take it?

120
00:08:26,500 --> 00:08:28,491
Good news...

121
00:08:29,940 --> 00:08:32,500
I receive calmly,

122
00:08:33,980 --> 00:08:35,698
even though
it makes me happy.

123
00:08:37,380 --> 00:08:38,575
That's for sure.

124
00:08:40,060 --> 00:08:43,098
As for bad news,

125
00:08:43,860 --> 00:08:45,259
I'm used to that.

126
00:08:47,180 --> 00:08:48,614
Doesn't it hurt the same?

127
00:08:50,060 --> 00:08:52,893
Some news is harder to take.

128
00:08:53,900 --> 00:08:55,379
For example, one day...

129
00:08:55,700 --> 00:08:59,580
I remember when I received
the news of my mother's death,

130
00:09:00,820 --> 00:09:03,016
I felt very deep pain.

131
00:09:11,220 --> 00:09:13,177
And when Che died.

132
00:09:16,740 --> 00:09:25,012
<i>(1928-1967) Ernesto “Che“ Guevara, Commander
of the Cuban Revolution, killed in Bolivia.</i>

133
00:09:26,180 --> 00:09:28,296
There are moments of grief...

134
00:09:30,060 --> 00:09:33,576
not only about news
but also about events

135
00:09:36,260 --> 00:09:37,819
you are involved in.

136
00:09:38,020 --> 00:09:41,376
He must have been frustrated in
the Elian Gonzalez in Miami affair.

137
00:09:42,540 --> 00:09:43,416
Well,

138
00:09:43,580 --> 00:09:46,413
that was the first time
we claimed someone.

139
00:09:48,020 --> 00:09:52,014
Illegal actions
have happened all the time.

140
00:09:53,380 --> 00:09:57,499
We committed ourselves to a fight
to win a battle that was not

141
00:09:57,660 --> 00:09:58,616
juridical...

142
00:09:59,340 --> 00:10:00,296
but political.

143
00:10:00,980 --> 00:10:03,210
I had a special feeling then.

144
00:10:04,540 --> 00:10:09,330
When we first received
the father's request

145
00:10:10,540 --> 00:10:12,099
to claim his son,

146
00:10:14,300 --> 00:10:17,019
I saw that from
the legal point of view

147
00:10:17,980 --> 00:10:19,698
we would never get support.

148
00:10:20,580 --> 00:10:24,972
But first I needed to know
what the father was like.

149
00:10:26,740 --> 00:10:29,209
Because to take on
a battle like that,

150
00:10:29,380 --> 00:10:31,132
I needed justification.

151
00:10:31,300 --> 00:10:33,018
Eight times

152
00:10:33,820 --> 00:10:36,096
the couple tried to have a baby.

153
00:10:39,220 --> 00:10:41,416
It was their eighth attempt.

154
00:10:42,540 --> 00:10:44,816
They cried...
I felt so sorry for them.

155
00:10:44,980 --> 00:10:46,254
And I realized...

156
00:10:47,620 --> 00:10:52,057
the cause was just,
that every effort should be made.

157
00:10:53,060 --> 00:10:54,414
And I was not wrong.

158
00:10:55,020 --> 00:10:58,012
I know that you don't use
psychiatrists very much.

159
00:10:58,740 --> 00:11:00,014
In all the grief he's had

160
00:11:00,180 --> 00:11:02,535
in his life, has he ever felt

161
00:11:02,700 --> 00:11:03,735
that he wanted to talk

162
00:11:03,900 --> 00:11:04,935
to a psychiatrist?

163
00:11:07,220 --> 00:11:09,450
That's never crossed my mind.

164
00:11:10,940 --> 00:11:13,056
- Never crossed your mind?
-Never.

165
00:11:14,500 --> 00:11:18,733
Perhaps it's something
to do with self-confidence.

166
00:11:19,340 --> 00:11:21,490
Quite honestly, I've never

167
00:11:21,660 --> 00:11:23,014
been asked that.

168
00:11:24,900 --> 00:11:25,890
Oliver...

169
00:11:26,740 --> 00:11:30,290
perhaps it's because
ever since I was a child

170
00:11:32,060 --> 00:11:33,016
I had to solve

171
00:11:35,020 --> 00:11:36,772
important problems by myself.

172
00:11:38,500 --> 00:11:41,856
I was sent to Santiago
de Cuba when I was

173
00:11:42,020 --> 00:11:42,896
5 or 6 years old.

174
00:11:44,580 --> 00:11:47,698
That was my first hard experience.

175
00:11:47,860 --> 00:11:50,978
I got used to solving
my own problems.

176
00:11:51,940 --> 00:11:55,092
So he said he became strong
in his head and his heart

177
00:11:55,260 --> 00:11:57,695
because his mother abandoned him?

178
00:11:59,340 --> 00:12:01,411
No, she was my ally,

179
00:12:02,340 --> 00:12:04,809
when I demanded to be sent
to boarding school.

180
00:12:07,020 --> 00:12:07,896
My father

181
00:12:08,060 --> 00:12:10,210
owned a lot of land.

182
00:12:10,380 --> 00:12:13,133
That was their livelihood.
But I

183
00:12:13,820 --> 00:12:15,891
demanded to be sent there.

184
00:12:17,580 --> 00:12:19,890
In the strongest possible terms.

185
00:12:21,660 --> 00:12:24,652
When I was in my second year
at university,

186
00:12:26,180 --> 00:12:28,137
I joined an expedition

187
00:12:29,740 --> 00:12:31,538
<i>to overthrow</i>

188
00:12:31,700 --> 00:12:34,374
Trujillo in Santo Domingo.

189
00:12:34,580 --> 00:12:36,810
Was he willing
to die at this age?

190
00:12:40,500 --> 00:12:41,171
Yes.

191
00:12:43,980 --> 00:12:45,493
Was he tortured?

192
00:12:46,580 --> 00:12:48,218
They wanted to torture me.

193
00:12:48,380 --> 00:12:49,176
But I was never tortured...

194
00:12:49,340 --> 00:12:51,217
After he was arrested,

195
00:12:51,380 --> 00:12:53,018
why didn't Batista shoot him?

196
00:12:53,340 --> 00:12:54,739
He knew he was a leader.

197
00:12:55,420 --> 00:13:00,176
He knew we didn't have
a penny, nor any resources.

198
00:13:02,380 --> 00:13:06,010
They underestimated...
They underestimated us.

199
00:13:07,460 --> 00:13:09,133
Do you believe in destiny or fate?

200
00:13:10,380 --> 00:13:11,814
I do not believe in destiny.

201
00:13:11,980 --> 00:13:13,095
To paraphrase

202
00:13:13,260 --> 00:13:14,773
Napoleon,
"The moment my destiny

203
00:13:14,940 --> 00:13:16,897
is over, I can be broken

204
00:13:17,060 --> 00:13:18,414
by a puff of wind

205
00:13:19,180 --> 00:13:21,569
or a match."
What does he think?

206
00:13:21,740 --> 00:13:23,174
I do not think like that.

207
00:13:24,140 --> 00:13:26,211
If I thought like that,

208
00:13:27,860 --> 00:13:31,490
it would appear as if I had arrived
at the end of my destiny.

209
00:13:33,420 --> 00:13:35,093
But we have never given up

210
00:13:35,260 --> 00:13:36,295
our fight.

211
00:13:37,620 --> 00:13:39,258
Not for one second.

212
00:13:40,420 --> 00:13:41,979
And the day

213
00:13:42,780 --> 00:13:45,454
I die, whatever the reason,

214
00:13:46,700 --> 00:13:48,054
I would not think...

215
00:13:49,100 --> 00:13:50,818
that it was destiny...

216
00:13:52,660 --> 00:13:53,730
that ended my work.

217
00:13:53,900 --> 00:13:56,130
I would think that
even after my death...

218
00:13:56,900 --> 00:13:58,174
I believe today...

219
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:02,176
in the future of Cuba,

220
00:14:02,340 --> 00:14:04,013
in the future of our cause.

221
00:14:05,100 --> 00:14:06,977
And perhaps that is the test.

222
00:14:12,700 --> 00:14:14,577
Why Hemingway?

223
00:14:15,060 --> 00:14:17,779
He was a winner for Fidel?

224
00:14:21,060 --> 00:14:23,370
Yes, I admire Hemingway very much.

225
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:25,850
But Hemingway
blew his brains out.

226
00:14:31,700 --> 00:14:33,771
According to his philosophy.

227
00:14:37,620 --> 00:14:40,817
If he were Salvador Allende and
they were closing in on his palace,

228
00:14:40,980 --> 00:14:42,618
would he commit suicide?

229
00:14:43,540 --> 00:14:44,575
I would fight

230
00:14:44,740 --> 00:14:46,060
to the death.

231
00:14:46,940 --> 00:14:50,217
And if the situation were such

232
00:14:51,180 --> 00:14:56,698
that my gun stopped working
or I didn't have...

233
00:14:57,900 --> 00:15:01,336
Yes, my decision would be to die.

234
00:15:01,820 --> 00:15:03,936
There's no doubt in my mind.

235
00:15:04,140 --> 00:15:06,416
At that moment
did he believe in God?

236
00:15:09,380 --> 00:15:11,212
I have never been a believer.

237
00:15:12,060 --> 00:15:13,619
Simply...

238
00:15:14,860 --> 00:15:17,773
because the methods used
in school to persuade me

239
00:15:20,180 --> 00:15:23,252
regarding religion
were dogmatic methods.

240
00:15:23,940 --> 00:15:25,658
So this is one life
and it's over?

241
00:15:27,340 --> 00:15:30,378
I am totally
convinced of that.

242
00:15:35,340 --> 00:15:40,210
Which version of your life would you
like to see for the closing chapter?

243
00:15:40,420 --> 00:15:41,296
Version one...

244
00:15:41,780 --> 00:15:43,612
You're a grandfather,

245
00:15:43,820 --> 00:15:45,379
many children...

246
00:15:46,540 --> 00:15:49,737
the benevolent patriarch,

247
00:15:51,900 --> 00:15:53,652
loved by the people,

248
00:15:55,180 --> 00:15:56,614
you die in bed...

249
00:15:59,500 --> 00:16:01,093
it's a great life.

250
00:16:02,740 --> 00:16:03,650
Or...

251
00:16:04,260 --> 00:16:06,979
the new world order happens,

252
00:16:07,660 --> 00:16:09,936
they throw Fidel in chains.

253
00:16:11,020 --> 00:16:15,810
With billions of people watching,
you give the most eloquent defense

254
00:16:17,420 --> 00:16:19,696
of human rights and dignity...

255
00:16:20,980 --> 00:16:22,129
ever heard.

256
00:16:23,380 --> 00:16:26,213
What would you do?
Version one or version two?

257
00:16:28,260 --> 00:16:29,534
Neither.

258
00:16:33,980 --> 00:16:38,372
I always try to be as rational
as possible in my thinking.

259
00:16:42,180 --> 00:16:45,218
I have an idea
of how relative glory can be.

260
00:16:45,580 --> 00:16:48,379
Look... Jose Marti
expressed it in a phrase.

261
00:16:48,660 --> 00:16:51,129
"All the glory in the world

262
00:16:52,500 --> 00:16:55,333
fits in a grain of corn."

263
00:16:57,380 --> 00:17:00,577
I have never thought about glory...

264
00:17:02,540 --> 00:17:06,738
never given a thought to how
