00:36:57,500 --> 00:37:02,336
With terrible consequences
for the health. Many women died.

535
00:37:03,180 --> 00:37:04,898
Now it is the woman's choice.

536
00:37:05,740 --> 00:37:08,698
So you don't have women who are
having 7 or 8 children anymore?

537
00:37:11,020 --> 00:37:14,854
That's not very common now
as women are more educated.

538
00:37:18,220 --> 00:37:21,372
They play a part in society.

539
00:37:24,500 --> 00:37:26,810
I think we've
spoiled their classes.

540
00:37:51,820 --> 00:37:53,094
You know, it's the uniform.

541
00:37:53,260 --> 00:37:57,140
If you came down with a pair of
Bermuda shorts, American flip-flops

542
00:37:57,300 --> 00:38:00,338
and an ugly T-shirt...
nobody would notice him.

543
00:38:09,460 --> 00:38:12,578
It's just a joke.
He doesn't smile.

544
00:38:13,100 --> 00:38:14,579
We will show...

545
00:38:17,940 --> 00:38:20,534
the security people
how to do their job.

546
00:38:25,500 --> 00:38:27,730
So that when Bush comes...

547
00:38:30,860 --> 00:38:33,693
If he travels here, you're
in trouble. I can tell you that.

548
00:38:36,620 --> 00:38:39,009
No problems.
We'd take care of him.

549
00:38:40,220 --> 00:38:42,814
No, he'll take care of you.
You'll be in the prison.

550
00:38:46,060 --> 00:38:47,937
He'll be back in prison.

551
00:38:49,580 --> 00:38:51,651
You can be sure of that.

552
00:38:55,740 --> 00:38:58,095
Is Gorbachev
a hero of his or not?

553
00:39:00,260 --> 00:39:01,295
He was...

554
00:39:02,540 --> 00:39:03,530
He had...

555
00:39:03,700 --> 00:39:05,134
good intentions.

556
00:39:05,300 --> 00:39:08,930
That country needed improvements,

557
00:39:09,100 --> 00:39:10,534
not destruction.

558
00:39:10,700 --> 00:39:11,929
Which Russian leader

559
00:39:12,100 --> 00:39:13,613
cut off the aid to Cuba?

560
00:39:14,820 --> 00:39:15,855
The Soviet leader

561
00:39:16,020 --> 00:39:19,172
who cut off aid to Cuba was...

562
00:39:19,340 --> 00:39:21,013
the U.S. government.

563
00:39:23,740 --> 00:39:24,855
Understand?

564
00:39:29,940 --> 00:39:31,453
I'll explain.

565
00:39:32,580 --> 00:39:34,457
When the USSR collapsed

566
00:39:36,140 --> 00:39:38,859
aid was interrupted.
Gorbachev was there.

567
00:39:39,780 --> 00:39:42,135
But he was less powerful.

568
00:39:45,700 --> 00:39:48,010
We had some agreements
from before him

569
00:39:51,620 --> 00:39:55,136
which expired when he was leader.

570
00:40:01,140 --> 00:40:02,972
He was drinking with...

571
00:40:03,300 --> 00:40:06,258
Khrushchev, he was drinking
with Brezhnev, he was drinking

572
00:40:06,660 --> 00:40:07,855
with Yeltsin...

573
00:40:08,620 --> 00:40:10,497
All three are major drinkers.

574
00:40:12,700 --> 00:40:14,293
Did he drink with them?

575
00:40:15,260 --> 00:40:18,059
No, it was difficult
to compete with Yeltsin.

576
00:40:20,700 --> 00:40:23,897
Which of these men
amused him most?

577
00:40:25,020 --> 00:40:27,739
I got on with Khrushchev best.

578
00:40:29,140 --> 00:40:32,610
Khrushchev was
the shrewd peasant type.

579
00:40:34,300 --> 00:40:36,416
He was the one who...

580
00:40:37,620 --> 00:40:40,931
initiated cooperation
with Cuba and felt sympathy

581
00:40:41,100 --> 00:40:42,090
for Cuba.

582
00:40:46,860 --> 00:40:47,930
<i>Revolution is</i>

583
00:40:48,100 --> 00:40:49,659
<i>for any country the most violent</i>

584
00:40:49,820 --> 00:40:50,651
<i>means of change,</i>

585
00:40:51,460 --> 00:40:53,610
<i>bringing as it does
death, destruction and hatred.</i>

586
00:40:54,620 --> 00:40:56,816
<i>The Cuban Revolution
ruled out one dictator,</i>

587
00:40:56,980 --> 00:40:59,654
<i>but it produced another...
Fidel Castro.</i>

588
00:41:01,460 --> 00:41:03,212
<i>Little did
the Cuban people suspect</i>

589
00:41:03,380 --> 00:41:04,654
<i>that Castro would betray</i>

590
00:41:04,820 --> 00:41:06,731
<i>their cause and deliver them
into the hands</i>

591
00:41:06,900 --> 00:41:08,652
<i>of the most ruthless
of all tyrannies...</i>

592
00:41:09,100 --> 00:41:11,330
<i>into the iron grip of communism.</i>

593
00:41:37,620 --> 00:41:40,692
When you were in
the guerrilla army up in the jungle,

594
00:41:40,860 --> 00:41:41,850
did anybody get fed up,

595
00:41:42,020 --> 00:41:44,978
anybody was like pissed off
and wanted to quit?

596
00:41:49,140 --> 00:41:50,050
Of course.

597
00:41:50,700 --> 00:41:52,611
Did people say, "This Castro
doesn't know what he's doing."?

598
00:41:52,780 --> 00:41:54,851
But nobody ever complained about

599
00:41:55,020 --> 00:41:56,249
the Castros directly.

600
00:41:56,820 --> 00:41:58,094
Some complained about...

601
00:41:59,980 --> 00:42:01,778
the hardships of the struggle,

602
00:42:02,180 --> 00:42:03,250
the great effort...

603
00:42:03,420 --> 00:42:05,013
what we would have at the end.

604
00:42:06,700 --> 00:42:09,089
Who inspired them?

605
00:42:09,260 --> 00:42:10,853
We were inspired by

606
00:42:11,020 --> 00:42:14,297
Cuban pro-independents,
who were brave fighters.

607
00:42:15,300 --> 00:42:16,734
Maximo Gomez, Marti,

608
00:42:16,900 --> 00:42:19,176
Maceo, who organized an invasion...

609
00:42:20,820 --> 00:42:23,255
30 years with machetes and horses...

610
00:42:23,940 --> 00:42:26,170
They were
our inspiration throughout.

611
00:42:26,340 --> 00:42:30,015
The tactics we used were
the result of observation

612
00:42:32,220 --> 00:42:33,893
and meditation

613
00:42:35,180 --> 00:42:36,739
and of inspiration.

614
00:42:40,020 --> 00:42:41,499
Tell me about Nixon.

615
00:42:45,180 --> 00:42:48,218
The first time I met him
was in March 1959.

616
00:42:49,580 --> 00:42:50,650
He was Vice President.

617
00:42:52,420 --> 00:42:53,740
We talked...

618
00:42:56,020 --> 00:42:59,615
I explained our situation to him,
shared my ideas with him...

619
00:43:01,780 --> 00:43:04,579
And he immediately
drafted a report.

620
00:43:06,580 --> 00:43:07,729
He wrote...

621
00:43:09,140 --> 00:43:10,289
that I was...

622
00:43:11,540 --> 00:43:12,371
a communist.

623
00:43:14,100 --> 00:43:16,376
At that time,
to talk about land reform

624
00:43:18,660 --> 00:43:21,049
identified you as a communist.

625
00:43:21,220 --> 00:43:22,574
From the very beginning

626
00:43:24,700 --> 00:43:27,374
he gave me the impression
of being a hypocrite...

627
00:43:29,220 --> 00:43:30,449
a small-minded politician...

628
00:43:32,180 --> 00:43:33,090
vain.

629
00:43:35,260 --> 00:43:36,455
Furthermore, it was he

630
00:43:36,620 --> 00:43:40,136
who recommended that
an expedition be organized

631
00:43:40,300 --> 00:43:41,290
to destroy us.

632
00:43:45,540 --> 00:43:47,338
At what point did he actually

633
00:43:47,500 --> 00:43:50,936
in his own thinking commit to the
Soviet Union as an ally

634
00:43:52,020 --> 00:43:52,737
and antagonize

635
00:43:52,900 --> 00:43:53,696
the United States?

636
00:43:53,860 --> 00:43:55,373
One: when

637
00:43:55,540 --> 00:43:57,417
we were deprived
of the sugar quota

638
00:43:58,580 --> 00:44:00,218
and were left
without a sugar market,

639
00:44:01,580 --> 00:44:03,457
and when the oil supply
was cut off.

640
00:44:05,660 --> 00:44:07,651
That was a political
economic moment.

641
00:44:08,940 --> 00:44:11,534
There was a sense of gratitude...

642
00:44:13,180 --> 00:44:17,060
It was not yet
a political commitment...

643
00:44:18,140 --> 00:44:19,414
nor military.

644
00:44:20,460 --> 00:44:21,734
But the fact is

645
00:44:21,900 --> 00:44:24,130
that the expedition was already

646
00:44:24,300 --> 00:44:25,734
being organized

647
00:44:27,820 --> 00:44:28,776
in Guatemala

648
00:44:29,860 --> 00:44:31,419
for the invasion.

649
00:44:33,140 --> 00:44:36,178
And so we started requesting

650
00:44:36,340 --> 00:44:40,777
the purchase of weapons
from the Soviet Union.

651
00:44:41,660 --> 00:44:43,094
Kennedy inherited

652
00:44:45,260 --> 00:44:48,969
the Eisenhower administration's
plans to invade Cuba.

653
00:44:49,860 --> 00:44:52,215
Plans in an advanced stage.

654
00:44:52,380 --> 00:44:55,020
Hardly 2 months passed before

655
00:44:55,220 --> 00:44:56,733
everything was under way.

656
00:44:58,100 --> 00:45:00,171
Kennedy did not have

657
00:45:00,340 --> 00:45:02,616
much experience.

658
00:45:03,100 --> 00:45:05,376
He trusted the U.S. institutions
too much.

659
00:45:07,540 --> 00:45:08,655
<i>These charges</i>

660
00:45:08,820 --> 00:45:10,811
<i>are totally false</i>

661
00:45:11,700 --> 00:45:13,577
<i>and I deny them categorically.</i>

662
00:45:14,780 --> 00:45:18,694
<i>The United States has committed
no aggression against Cuba,</i>

663
00:45:18,860 --> 00:45:21,739
<i>and no offensive
has been launched from Florida</i>

664
00:45:21,900 --> 00:45:22,970
<i>or from any</i>

665
00:45:23,140 --> 00:45:25,131
<i>other part of the United States.</i>

666
00:45:47,060 --> 00:45:48,289
Actually...

667
00:45:48,940 --> 00:45:51,250
the reason for the missiles here

668
00:45:51,420 --> 00:45:54,412
was that the Soviets
had information

669
00:45:56,220 --> 00:45:58,018
that there was a plan

670
00:45:59,700 --> 00:46:01,134
to invade Cuba.

671
00:46:02,300 --> 00:46:05,133
Khrushchev had made
a deep commitment to Cuba.

672
00:46:07,060 --> 00:46:10,371
Even at the time
of the invasion he made

673
00:46:10,540 --> 00:46:12,213
very strong statements.

674
00:46:14,940 --> 00:46:19,411
He spoke about
strategic missiles, implying

675
00:46:19,580 --> 00:46:21,730
that Cuba would be supported.

676
00:46:21,900 --> 00:46:25,131
And there was a moral factor
that had to be considered.

677
00:46:26,220 --> 00:46:28,177
We did not like the idea...

678
00:46:29,420 --> 00:46:33,015
We would have taken
whatever risks were necessary

679
00:46:35,780 --> 00:46:36,576
rather than

680
00:46:37,620 --> 00:46:41,534
appear as a Soviet military base
in the Western hemisphere.

681
00:46:43,660 --> 00:46:46,652
So, from the military
point of view,

682
00:46:46,820 --> 00:46:48,572
things were very bad.

683
00:46:48,740 --> 00:46:51,778
They'd allowed the Americans
to use their surveillance planes

684
00:46:51,940 --> 00:46:54,329
to survey the whole area
and locate the missiles.

685
00:46:57,820 --> 00:47:00,619
They put our country
in great danger. We...

686
00:47:00,780 --> 00:47:03,215
thought we would be obliterated.

687
00:47:04,500 --> 00:47:07,014
We would be the first to disappear.

688
00:47:09,420 --> 00:47:10,615
Your critics in America

689
00:47:10,780 --> 00:47:13,738
and the historians
continue to say that

690
00:47:13,900 --> 00:47:15,777
in the October 26th letter
to Khrushchev

691
00:47:16,300 --> 00:47:18,337
you called for nuclear war.

692
00:47:19,620 --> 00:47:20,849
Socialism or death.

693
00:47:21,460 --> 00:47:22,859
It's been interpreted that way.

694
00:47:24,580 --> 00:47:26,730
I did not ask them to attack.

695
00:47:27,900 --> 00:47:30,653
I said,
"If this country is attacked...

696
00:47:33,260 --> 00:47:36,378
If this country is attacked

697
00:47:37,820 --> 00:47:42,576
with 40,000 Soviet troops..."
There was an agreement...

698
00:47:44,460 --> 00:47:47,657
My conviction was that

699
00:47:48,820 --> 00:47:50,572
after the invasion,

700
00:47:53,380 --> 00:47:57,931
the Americans would not
take long to launch an attack.

701
00:47:59,020 --> 00:48:00,579
We did not have
a Russian translator.

702
00:48:01,980 --> 00:48:05,291
There was an ambassador

703
00:48:06,660 --> 00:48:08,856
who spoke Spanish

704
00:48:10,260 --> 00:48:13,059
very poorly. So,

705
00:48:13,220 --> 00:48:15,291
that note, I...

706
00:48:17,220 --> 00:48:18,654
I doubt

707
00:48:18,820 --> 00:48:20,618
that he received a clear message.

708
00:48:21,940 --> 00:48:23,772
I can only imagine

709
00:48:25,780 --> 00:48:28,249
what the ambassador translated.

710
00:48:30,940 --> 00:48:32,089
After,

711
00:48:32,260 --> 00:48:33,694
Khrushchev sent me a letter

712
00:48:34,900 --> 00:48:37,369
defending himself
from my accusations.

713
00:48:38,140 --> 00:48:41,451
He said he had obtained a guarantee
from the U.S. not to invade Cuba.

714
00:48:45,100 --> 00:48:46,579
A verbal guarantee.

715
00:48:47,700 --> 00:48:50,852
And he said we had suggested

716
00:48:52,780 --> 00:48:54,293
a first strike.

717
00:48:58,620 --> 00:49:00,850
<i>We will not prematurely
or unnecessarily</i>

718
00:49:01,460 --> 00:49:04,179
<i>risk the course
of worldwide nuclear war</i>

719
00:49:04,940 --> 00:49:06,738
<i>in which even the fruits
of victory would be</i>

720
00:49:06,900 --> 00:49:08,174
<i>ashes in our mouth.</i>

721
00:49:08,780 --> 00:49:11,294
<i>But neither will we shrink
from that risk</i>

722
00:49:11,460 --> 00:49:13,178
<i>at any time it must be faced.</i>

723
00:49:28,740 --> 00:49:30,651
Kennedy committed himself.

724
00:49:32,220 --> 00:49:35,576
He believed it because...

725
00:49:35,740 --> 00:49:36,935
It was a game of words.

726
00:49:38,980 --> 00:49:41,130
Khrushchev resorted to

727
00:49:41,300 --> 00:49:43,940
the naive and superficial notion...

728
00:49:46,660 --> 00:49:49,049
of the intentions behind

729
00:49:49,220 --> 00:49:50,449
those weapons...

730
00:49:53,300 --> 00:49:56,531
He said he had no intention
of using them, for him...

731
00:49:57,420 --> 00:49:59,297
That was the argument he used.

732
00:50:00,940 --> 00:50:03,375
Mr. Castro could not
have pushed the trigger?

733
00:50:07,460 --> 00:50:13,456
No, if we had done nothing...
we were afraid that they would

734
00:50:13,620 --> 00:50:14,655
be destroyed.

735
00:50:16,500 --> 00:50:21,574
And we would be left
with all the radioactivity.

736
00:50:39,140 --> 00:50:41,939
What should Khrushchev
have asked for Cuba?

737
00:50:43,380 --> 00:50:45,815
The return of Guantanamo base.

738
00:50:46,500 --> 00:50:48,411
An end to the blockade.

739
00:50:49,380 --> 00:50:52,133
An end to the terrorist attacks...

740
00:50:53,620 --> 00:50:54,769
Five points.

741
00:50:57,580 --> 00:51:01,574
I think the sticking point for
Kennedy was that if Cuba existed as

742
00:51:01,740 --> 00:51:04,573
a Socialist model in the hemisphere
it would have been dangerous.

743
00:51:05,460 --> 00:51:07,610
The Russians understood that.

744
00:51:09,420 --> 00:51:12,173
So they put
their own interests first.

745
00:51:16,260 --> 00:51:19,173
Yes, and I wrote about that.

746
00:51:21,180 --> 00:51:22,295
They could not
have won the point

747
00:51:22,460 --> 00:51:25,054
because America
would always hate Cuba...

748
00:51:25,420 --> 00:51:27,331
Great tension
was created worldwide.

749
00:51:28,860 --> 00:51:32,649
No one in the world was willing
to have a nuclear war

750
00:51:34,180 --> 00:51:36,456
over a military base there.

751
00:51:36,940 --> 00:51:39,250
Or an economic blockade of Cuba.

752
00:51:42,300 --> 00:51:44,450
No one would have gone
to war for that.

753
00:51:47,300 --> 00:51:48,529
And we were new...

754
00:51:52,060 --> 00:51:54,893
We could not pretend
to have more experience.

755
00:51:56,820 --> 00:51:58,379
We didn't understand

756
00:51:58,540 --> 00:52:00,497
the balance of power,

757
00:52:00,740 --> 00:52:03,459
what military might they had...

758
00:52:03,620 --> 00:52:05,133
At the time of the invasion,

759
00:52:07,220 --> 00:52:08,813
the Revolution was 2 years old.

760
00:52:10,420 --> 00:52:14,653
At the time of
the missile crisis, 3 years.

761
00:52:17,300 --> 00:52:21,134
I think that we did
what we had to do.

762
00:52:22,580 --> 00:52:24,651
And we did it relatively well.

763
00:52:24,820 --> 00:52:28,654
But I do not think
we could have known

764
00:52:31,060 --> 00:52:35,372
how erratic
our friends and allies

765
00:52:35,540 --> 00:52:37,099
could be.
They did not understand

766
00:52:37,260 --> 00:52:38,409
the Third World.

767
00:52:39,700 --> 00:52:41,816
Nor the theater of operations.

768
00:52:43,980 --> 00:52:48,099
They only thought about tank
brigades, artillery,

769
00:52:48,260 --> 00:52:50,615
motorized infantry,

770
00:52:51,940 --> 00:52:53,453
conventional troops.

771
00:52:53,620 --> 00:52:55,213
And irregular warfare
cannot be fought

772
00:52:56,500 --> 00:52:58,093
with conventional troops.

773
00:52:58,260 --> 00:52:59,739
They are only for parades.

774
00:52:59,900 --> 00:53:01,049
But we engaged

775
00:53:02,700 --> 00:53:03,974
in irregular warfare

776
00:53:04,140 --> 00:53:06,370
and we defeated our enemies.

777
00:53:24,660 --> 00:53:26,731
If Mr. Castro knew

778
00:53:26,900 --> 00:53:29,016
that the CIA
had been behind the coup

779
00:53:29,180 --> 00:53:31,979
of 54, then he had
more reason not to trust

780
00:53:32,140 --> 00:53:33,016
the United States.

781
00:53:33,180 --> 00:53:37,299
Especially knowing how the United
States had acted historically.

782
00:53:37,700 --> 00:53:41,489
But many...
It was not the only intervention.

783
00:53:42,220 --> 00:53:43,654
There was Santo Domingo...

784
00:53:43,820 --> 00:53:46,130
And in Central America

785
00:53:46,300 --> 00:53:47,813
on several occasions.

786
00:53:47,980 --> 00:53:50,256
The CIA already existed,
of course.

787
00:53:52,140 --> 00:53:53,892
And he knew all this?

788
00:53:55,060 --> 00:53:57,256
Yes, everyone knew about it.

789
00:53:57,500 --> 00:53:59,377
Except Americans.

790
00:54:00,300 --> 00:54:03,816
Because they told
the Americans one thing...

791
00:54:04,620 --> 00:54:07,009
That it was
a Communist government,

792
00:54:07,460 --> 00:54:10,691
and a danger to
the national security of the U.S.

793
00:54:11,740 --> 00:54:13,777
And that is a sacred expression.

794
00:54:15,260 --> 00:54:17,410
Whenever it is invoked,
there is a reaction.

795
00:54:18,420 --> 00:54:21,378
A conditioned reflex.

796
00:54:22,220 --> 00:54:25,451
"Such and such a thing
is a threat to national security."

